---

<PageShell
  title="Netherlands Entrepreneur Visa 2026: Startup Visa, Self-Employed & DAFT Guide"
  description="Complete guide to Netherlands entrepreneur visa options: Startup Visa, Self-Employed Residence Permit, and DAFT. Points system, insurance requirements, and application process."
  headline="Netherlands Entrepreneur Visa: Startup, Self-Employed & DAFT Guide"
  subheadline="Everything you need to know about starting a business in the Netherlands—Startup Visa for innovators, Self-Employed permit with points system, DAFT for Americans, and mandatory Dutch health insurance."
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Compare International Insurance"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/cigna-global"
  heroImage="/images/countries/netherlands-hero-bg.png"
>

  <!-- Trust Signals -->
  <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-4 mb-8 text-sm text-neutral-600">
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1">
      <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-green-600" fill="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 20 20"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M10 18a8 8 0 100-16 8 8 0 000 16zm3.707-9.293a1 1 0 00-1.414-1.414L9 10.586 7.707 9.293a1 1 0 00-1.414 1.414l2 2a1 1 0 001.414 0l4-4z" clip-rule="evenodd"></path></svg>
      Updated February 2026
    </span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1">
      <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-green-600" fill="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 20 20"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M10 18a8 8 0 100-16 8 8 0 000 16zm3.707-9.293a1 1 0 00-1.414-1.414L9 10.586 7.707 9.293a1 1 0 00-1.414 1.414l2 2a1 1 0 001.414 0l4-4z" clip-rule="evenodd"></path></svg>
      Official IND Requirements
    </span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1">
      <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-green-600" fill="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 20 20"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M10 18a8 8 0 100-16 8 8 0 000 16zm3.707-9.293a1 1 0 00-1.414-1.414L9 10.586 7.707 9.293a1 1 0 00-1.414 1.414l2 2a1 1 0 001.414 0l4-4z" clip-rule="evenodd"></path></svg>
      Strong Startup Ecosystem
    </span>
  </div>

  <!-- Section: Overview -->
  <section id="overview" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Overview</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      The Netherlands does not offer a "Golden Visa" investment-for-residency program like Spain or Portugal. Instead, entrepreneurs have several pathways to Dutch residence—each requiring you to actively run a business rather than simply invest capital. The most popular routes are the Startup Visa for innovative entrepreneurs, the Self-Employed Residence Permit with a points-based evaluation, and DAFT for US, Japanese, and Swiss citizens.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-4">
      What makes the Netherlands attractive isn't passive investment—it's one of Europe's strongest startup ecosystems, business-friendly regulations, a highly educated English-speaking workforce, and strategic access to EU markets. Cities like Amsterdam, Rotterdam, The Hague, and Eindhoven (the "Brainport" tech hub) are magnets for international entrepreneurs.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6 mb-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary-900 mb-3">Key Facts: Netherlands Entrepreneur Visas</h3>
      <ul class="space-y-2 text-primary-800">
        <li>• <strong>Startup Visa:</strong> 1-year residence to build innovative startup with Dutch facilitator</li>
        <li>• <strong>Self-Employed Permit:</strong> Points-based system (100 points needed); 2-year permit</li>
        <li>• <strong>DAFT:</strong> US/Japan/Swiss citizens; €4,500 minimum investment; 2-year permit</li>
        <li>• <strong>Health insurance:</strong> Dutch basic insurance (basisverzekering) MANDATORY</li>
        <li>• <strong>Path to permanent residence:</strong> 5 years continuous legal residence</li>
        <li>• <strong>Path to citizenship:</strong> 5 years (or 3 if married to Dutch citizen)</li>
        <li>• <strong>30% ruling:</strong> Potential tax benefit for skilled migrants</li>
        <li>• <strong>Processing time:</strong> Up to 90 days (IND)</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Why Choose the Netherlands?</h3>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
      <div class="border border-green-200 bg-green-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-green-900 mb-3">Advantages</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-green-800">
          <li>• Top-ranked startup ecosystem in Europe</li>
          <li>• 90%+ English proficiency—easy to operate</li>
          <li>• Strategic location: gateway to 450M EU consumers</li>
          <li>• Excellent infrastructure (airports, ports, digital)</li>
          <li>• 30% ruling tax benefit available</li>
          <li>• Path to citizenship in 5 years</li>
          <li>• World-class healthcare system</li>
          <li>• High quality of life</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-amber-200 bg-amber-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-3">Considerations</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-amber-800">
          <li>• No passive investment route—must run a business</li>
          <li>• Points system can be challenging to navigate</li>
          <li>• Startup Visa requires finding a recognized facilitator</li>
          <li>• High cost of living (especially Amsterdam)</li>
          <li>• Mandatory Dutch health insurance (~€1,800/year)</li>
          <li>• Housing market is extremely competitive</li>
          <li>• Must learn Dutch for citizenship (NT2 exam)</li>
          <li>• Weather is... Dutch</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4">
      <p class="text-blue-800">
        <strong>No Golden Visa here:</strong> Unlike Spain, Portugal, or Greece, the Netherlands does not offer residency through real estate or passive investment. Every entrepreneur pathway requires active business involvement. If you want to invest €500,000+ and visit occasionally, the Netherlands isn't the right choice. If you want to build a company in Europe's most connected economy, keep reading.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Quick Decision Guide -->
  <section id="quick-decision" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Quick Decision Guide</h2>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
      <div class="bg-green-50 border border-green-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-green-900 mb-3">Netherlands is Right For You If:</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-green-800">
          <li>✓ You want to actively build a business in Europe</li>
          <li>✓ You have an innovative product or service</li>
          <li>✓ You value English-friendly business environment</li>
          <li>✓ You want access to EU markets from day one</li>
          <li>✓ You're comfortable with higher living costs</li>
          <li>✓ You're a US citizen (DAFT is straightforward)</li>
          <li>✓ You want a relatively fast path to citizenship</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-3">Consider Other Options If:</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-amber-800">
          <li>• You want passive investment residency (try Portugal, Spain)</li>
          <li>• You don't have an innovative or points-qualifying business</li>
          <li>• You need lower cost of living</li>
          <li>• You want to minimize tax obligations</li>
          <li>• You prefer warmer climate</li>
          <li>• You're not comfortable with mandatory Dutch insurance</li>
          <li>• You want minimal involvement in daily business operations</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Which Pathway is Right For You?</h3>

    <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-6">
      <table class="w-full text-sm">
        <thead class="bg-neutral-100">
          <tr>
            <th class="px-4 py-2 text-left">Pathway</th>
            <th class="px-4 py-2 text-left">Best For</th>
            <th class="px-4 py-2 text-left">Key Requirement</th>
            <th class="px-4 py-2 text-left">Duration</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr class="border-b">
            <td class="px-4 py-2 font-medium">Startup Visa</td>
            <td class="px-4 py-2">Tech founders, innovators</td>
            <td class="px-4 py-2">Dutch facilitator (incubator)</td>
            <td class="px-4 py-2">1 year</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="border-b bg-neutral-50">
            <td class="px-4 py-2 font-medium">Self-Employed</td>
            <td class="px-4 py-2">Experienced entrepreneurs</td>
            <td class="px-4 py-2">100 points in evaluation</td>
            <td class="px-4 py-2">2 years</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="border-b">
            <td class="px-4 py-2 font-medium">DAFT</td>
            <td class="px-4 py-2">US/Japan/Swiss citizens</td>
            <td class="px-4 py-2">€4,500 readily available</td>
            <td class="px-4 py-2">2 years</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="border-b bg-neutral-50">
            <td class="px-4 py-2 font-medium">Intra-Company Transfer</td>
            <td class="px-4 py-2">Corporate executives/specialists</td>
            <td class="px-4 py-2">Employed by multinational</td>
            <td class="px-4 py-2">Up to 3 years</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4">
      <p class="text-blue-800">
        <strong>If you're American:</strong> The DAFT (Dutch-American Friendship Treaty) is your simplest path. With just €4,500 readily available and a viable business plan, you can get a 2-year renewable residence permit. It's one of the easiest entrepreneur visas in Europe for US citizens.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Visa Requirements -->
  <section id="visa-requirements" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Visa Requirements</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      The Netherlands offers several pathways for entrepreneurs. Each has distinct requirements, and there's no "one size fits all" option. We'll cover the most common routes: Startup Visa, Self-Employed Residence Permit, and DAFT.
    </p>

    <ComparisonTable columns={visaPathColumns} rows={visaPathRows} />

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-8 mb-3">Startup Visa (Most Popular for Innovators)</h3>

    <p class="mb-4">
      The Startup Visa is designed for entrepreneurs with innovative products or services who want to launch in the Netherlands. You get 1 year to develop your startup with support from a recognized Dutch facilitator (incubator, accelerator, or innovation hub).
    </p>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
      <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Requirements</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-neutral-700">
          <li>• <strong>Innovative product or service:</strong> Must be new to the Dutch market</li>
          <li>• <strong>Recognized facilitator:</strong> Must sign support agreement</li>
          <li>• <strong>Sufficient funds:</strong> To support yourself during startup year</li>
          <li>• <strong>Valid passport</strong></li>
          <li>• <strong>Clean criminal record</strong></li>
          <li>• <strong>Health insurance:</strong> International during application, then Dutch</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">What Facilitators Provide</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-neutral-700">
          <li>• Official support letter for IND</li>
          <li>• Mentorship and guidance</li>
          <li>• Workspace (often shared office)</li>
          <li>• Network access and introductions</li>
          <li>• Help navigating Dutch business registration</li>
          <li>• Some offer investment or funding connections</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p class="mb-6">
      <strong>After 1 year:</strong> If your startup is viable, you apply for a Self-Employed Residence Permit to continue. If it fails, you typically need to leave (though some facilitators help transition to other visa types).
    </p>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4 mb-8">
      <p class="text-blue-800">
        <strong>Finding a facilitator:</strong> The RVO (Netherlands Enterprise Agency) maintains a list of recognized facilitators at <em>english.rvo.nl</em>. Popular options include Rockstart, HighTechXL (Eindhoven), StartupBootcamp, and Yes!Delft. Some are free; others charge fees or take equity.
      </p>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Self-Employed Residence Permit (Points System)</h3>

    <p class="mb-4">
      For entrepreneurs without a tech startup or those coming from countries without a special treaty, the Self-Employed Residence Permit uses a points-based evaluation. You need at least 100 points across three categories.
    </p>

    <ComparisonTable columns={pointsColumns} rows={pointsRows} />

    <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-4 my-6">
      <p class="text-amber-800">
        <strong>Points system reality:</strong> Scoring 100 points is challenging for first-time entrepreneurs. The system favors applicants with significant experience, strong business plans, and clear added value to the Netherlands. Most successful applicants have 10+ years of business experience or bring investment/job creation.
      </p>
    </div>

    <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How Points Are Evaluated</h4>

    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 mb-6">
      <li><strong>Personal experience:</strong> Education level, years of entrepreneurial experience, previous business success</li>
      <li><strong>Business plan:</strong> Market research, financial projections, competitive analysis, viability assessment</li>
      <li><strong>Added value:</strong> Does your business bring innovation, jobs, or investment to the Netherlands? Does it fill a gap in the market?</li>
    </ul>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">DAFT (Dutch-American Friendship Treaty)</h3>

    <p class="mb-4">
      The DAFT is a 1956 treaty that allows US citizens (and by extension, Japanese and Swiss citizens under similar arrangements) to obtain Dutch self-employed residence with minimal requirements. It's by far the easiest path for Americans.
    </p>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
      <div class="border border-green-200 bg-green-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-green-900 mb-3">DAFT Requirements</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-green-800">
          <li>✓ US, Japanese, or Swiss citizenship</li>
          <li>✓ €4,500 readily available (not invested)</li>
          <li>✓ Valid business plan</li>
          <li>✓ Registered with Dutch Chamber of Commerce (KvK)</li>
          <li>✓ Valid passport</li>
          <li>✓ No criminal record</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-blue-200 bg-blue-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-blue-900 mb-3">DAFT Benefits</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-blue-800">
          <li>• No points system evaluation</li>
          <li>• Lower barrier than Self-Employed permit</li>
          <li>• 2-year permit, renewable indefinitely</li>
          <li>• Spouse can work for any employer</li>
          <li>• Children can attend school</li>
          <li>• Path to permanent residence (5 years)</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-green-50 border border-green-200 rounded-lg p-4">
      <p class="text-green-800">
        <strong>DAFT catch:</strong> The €4,500 must be "readily available"—in a Dutch bank account or accessible immediately. You don't need to invest it, just prove you have it. Many DAFT applicants are freelancers, consultants, or small business owners. The bar is intentionally low for treaty citizens.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Insurance Requirements -->
  <section id="insurance-requirements" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Insurance Requirements</h2>

    <div class="bg-red-50 border border-red-200 rounded-lg p-6 mb-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-red-900 mb-2">Dutch Basic Insurance is Legally Mandatory</h3>
      <p class="text-red-800">
        Once you register as a resident in the Netherlands, you are legally required to obtain Dutch basic health insurance (basisverzekering) within 4 months. This is not optional—it's enforced by law. International insurance does NOT satisfy this requirement. Failure to obtain Dutch insurance results in automatic enrollment and backdated premiums.
      </p>
    </div>

    <p class="mb-4">
      The Netherlands has a unique healthcare system that combines mandatory private insurance with public regulation. Everyone pays roughly the same premium for basic coverage (around €130-160/month), plus a mandatory annual deductible (eigen risico) of €385. Insurers cannot refuse you or charge more based on health status.
    </p>

    <ComparisonTable columns={insuranceColumns} rows={insuranceRows} />

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-8 mb-3">Two-Phase Insurance Strategy</h3>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Most entrepreneur visa applicants need insurance in two phases:
    </p>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
      <div class="border border-blue-200 bg-blue-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-blue-900 mb-3">Phase 1: Application & Arrival</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-blue-800">
          <li>• Use international insurance (Cigna Global, Allianz Care)</li>
          <li>• Required for visa application</li>
          <li>• Covers you until municipal registration</li>
          <li>• Can cancel once Dutch insurance starts</li>
          <li>• Typically 1-3 months</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-green-200 bg-green-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-green-900 mb-3">Phase 2: Dutch Resident</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-green-800">
          <li>• Obtain Dutch basic insurance (zorgverzekering)</li>
          <li>• Legally required within 4 months</li>
          <li>• Choose any Dutch insurer</li>
          <li>• Add supplementary insurance as needed</li>
          <li>• Annual open enrollment in November-December</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">What Dutch Basic Insurance Covers</h3>

    <p class="mb-4">
      The basic package (basispakket) is standardized across all Dutch insurers—you get the same coverage regardless of which company you choose. Differences are in service, apps, and supplementary packages.
    </p>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
      <div class="border border-green-200 bg-green-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-green-900 mb-3">Included in Basic Insurance</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-green-800">
          <li>✓ GP (huisarts) visits and referrals</li>
          <li>✓ Hospital care and surgery</li>
          <li>✓ Specialist consultations</li>
          <li>✓ Prescription medications</li>
          <li>✓ Maternity care and childbirth</li>
          <li>✓ Mental health care (up to limits)</li>
          <li>✓ Ambulance and emergency care</li>
          <li>✓ Medical devices and prosthetics</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-amber-200 bg-amber-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-3">NOT Included (Need Supplementary)</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-amber-800">
          <li>• Dental care (adults)</li>
          <li>• Physiotherapy (first 20 sessions/year)</li>
          <li>• Glasses and contact lenses</li>
          <li>• Alternative medicine (acupuncture, etc.)</li>
          <li>• Extensive mental health care</li>
          <li>• Cosmetic procedures</li>
          <li>• Most vaccinations for travel</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4">
      <p class="text-blue-800">
        <strong>The mandatory deductible (eigen risico):</strong> In 2026, the first €385 of most healthcare costs (excluding GP visits and maternity) come out of your pocket. You can voluntarily increase this to €885 for lower monthly premiums—a common choice for healthy people. Think of it like a US deductible.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

