  <!-- Section: Common Mistakes -->
  <section id="mistakes" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Thinking the Startup Visa is for Any Business</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">The Startup Visa specifically requires an "innovative" product or service. Consulting firms, restaurants, design agencies, and traditional businesses don't qualify—even if they're profitable. You need a genuinely new product, technology, or business model. If you're starting a conventional business, look at Self-Employed or DAFT instead.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Expecting to Keep International Insurance</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Once you're registered as a Dutch resident, international health insurance does NOT satisfy the legal requirement. You must obtain Dutch basic insurance within 4 months. The government will auto-enroll you and backdate premiums if you don't. Budget for this as an ongoing cost (~€1,800-2,400/year including deductible).</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Underestimating the Points System</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">The Self-Employed permit points system is genuinely difficult. Most first-time applicants don't score 100 points without significant preparation. Work with an immigration lawyer who can assess your likelihood before you apply. The €350 application fee is non-refundable if rejected.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Not Having Housing Arranged</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">The Netherlands, especially Amsterdam, has a severe housing shortage. You cannot register at the municipality without a valid address. Arrange housing before arriving—whether a rental contract, serviced apartment, or staying with someone who will register you temporarily. Don't assume you'll "figure it out" after landing.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Forgetting About Dutch Tax Obligations</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">As a Dutch resident, you're taxed on worldwide income. The Netherlands has high income tax rates (up to 49.5%). The 30% ruling can help if you qualify, but not everyone does. Consult a Dutch tax advisor before moving—especially if you have investments, property abroad, or multiple income sources.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Healthcare in Netherlands -->
  <section id="healthcare" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Healthcare in Netherlands</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      The Dutch healthcare system consistently ranks among the best in Europe. It combines mandatory private insurance with government regulation to ensure universal coverage and controlled costs. As a resident, you'll have access to high-quality care—though it works differently than systems you may be used to.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">How Dutch Healthcare Works</h3>

    <p class="mb-4">
      The cornerstone of Dutch healthcare is the huisarts (general practitioner/GP). Your GP is the gatekeeper to all other care—you need a referral to see specialists. This is different from countries where you can go directly to specialists.
    </p>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
      <div class="border border-green-200 bg-green-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-green-900 mb-3">What You'll Appreciate</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-green-800">
          <li>✓ High quality, modern facilities</li>
          <li>✓ Excellent doctor training and standards</li>
          <li>✓ Most medical staff speak English well</li>
          <li>✓ Standardized basic coverage for everyone</li>
          <li>✓ Cannot be denied coverage or charged more for health</li>
          <li>✓ GP visits are fully covered (no deductible)</li>
          <li>✓ Prescription system well-organized</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-amber-200 bg-amber-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-3">What Takes Adjustment</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-amber-800">
          <li>• GPs tend toward conservative treatment ("wait and see")</li>
          <li>• Cannot see specialists without GP referral</li>
          <li>• Waiting times for non-urgent specialist care</li>
          <li>• First €385/year costs come from your pocket</li>
          <li>• Some expats find GPs dismissive of minor complaints</li>
          <li>• Mental health care can have long wait lists</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Registering with a GP</h3>

    <p class="mb-4">
      One of your first tasks as a new resident is registering with a local GP (huisarts). This can be challenging in Amsterdam and other major cities where popular practices are often full. Tips:
    </p>

    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 mb-6">
      <li><strong>Register early:</strong> Start looking for a GP before you need one</li>
      <li><strong>Check for English-speaking practices:</strong> Look for "expat-friendly" GPs, especially in international areas</li>
      <li><strong>Be persistent:</strong> If one practice is full, try the next one in your neighborhood</li>
      <li><strong>Consider gezondheidscentrum:</strong> Health centers with multiple GPs often have more availability</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4">
      <p class="text-blue-800">
        <strong>For serious or specialist care:</strong> Dutch hospitals are excellent. For non-emergency specialist care, expect wait times of 2-6 weeks depending on specialty and urgency. The system prioritizes based on medical need. If you need faster access, supplementary insurance can provide private options at additional cost.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I invest in Dutch real estate to get residency like in Spain or Portugal?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          No. The Netherlands does not have a Golden Visa or investment-for-residency program. All entrepreneur visa routes require you to actively run a business. If you want passive investment residency in Europe, consider Spain (€500,000), Portugal (fund investment), or Greece (€250,000-500,000 property).
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What happens after my Startup Visa year ends?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          If your startup is viable (generating revenue or on track), you apply for a Self-Employed Residence Permit to continue. Your facilitator will provide an assessment. If the startup failed, you typically need to leave the Netherlands—though some people transition to other visa types (employment, partnership) if circumstances allow. The year is genuinely meant for building, not permanent residence.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can my spouse work in the Netherlands?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes, in most cases. Spouses of DAFT holders receive full work authorization—they can work for any Dutch employer. Spouses of Startup Visa and Self-Employed permit holders can also work, though exact conditions vary. Both you and your spouse will need Dutch health insurance once registered.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I need to learn Dutch?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Not for business—the Netherlands is so English-friendly that many entrepreneurs operate entirely in English. However, you will need Dutch for citizenship. The NT2 exam (Dutch language) is required for naturalization. Budget time to learn over your 5 years of residence. Daily life is easier without Dutch, but integration is smoother with it.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What is the 30% ruling and do I qualify?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          The 30% ruling is a tax benefit where 30% of your gross salary is tax-free, reducing your effective tax rate significantly. It's designed for "skilled migrants" recruited from abroad. Entrepreneurs may qualify if they take a salary from their own company and meet specific expertise requirements. Discuss with a Dutch tax advisor—the rules are complex and the benefit is being phased down.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How difficult is it to get permanent residence and citizenship?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Permanent residence requires 5 years of continuous legal residence, sufficient income, and passing a civic integration exam (inburgeringsexamen). Citizenship also requires 5 years and the NT2 Dutch language exam. Unlike some EU countries, the Netherlands allows dual citizenship in many cases—check your home country's rules. The path is straightforward if you maintain your business and stay compliant.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Final Verdict -->
  <section id="verdict" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Final Verdict</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      The Netherlands offers genuine opportunity for entrepreneurs willing to actively build a business—but it's not a Golden Visa destination. If you're looking for passive investment residency, look elsewhere. If you want to launch a company in one of Europe's strongest economies with English fluency, top talent, and EU market access, the Netherlands delivers.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-4">
      For Americans, the DAFT is remarkably accessible: €4,500 readily available and a viable business plan gets you a renewable 2-year residence permit. For tech founders with innovative products, the Startup Visa provides 12 months of incubator support and mentorship. For experienced entrepreneurs who can demonstrate value to the Dutch economy, the Self-Employed permit offers a path—though the 100-point threshold requires preparation.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-6">
      The catch is mandatory Dutch health insurance and the high cost of living—budget €2,000-3,000/year for healthcare and €18,000-30,000/year for housing in major cities. These are ongoing costs that you can't avoid. But for the right entrepreneur, the Netherlands provides a stable, connected, English-speaking base in the heart of Europe.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary-900 mb-3">Bottom Line</h3>
      <p class="text-primary-800 mb-4">
        The Netherlands rewards active entrepreneurs over passive investors. DAFT makes it easy for Americans; the Startup Visa supports genuine innovators; the Self-Employed permit is tough but achievable with preparation. Budget for mandatory Dutch health insurance (€130-160/month plus €385 deductible) and the reality that this is not a low-cost destination. Work with immigration professionals for the points-based routes.
      </p>
